segments.text: This is our second interview with General Harrington.
Today is August 13, I believe.
This is Terry Anderson.
Last time we got through your command of the 823rd Air Division in Florida, and then we were just starting.
your military assistance advisory group in Japan.
Let's continue talking about that.
Tell me what your functions and duties were there.
Well, your functions as the Air Force chief of the MAG group, military assistance group, was to provide technical assistance to the
Chief of Staff of the Japanese Air Defense Force.
Oh, that's right, yeah.
And to also provide logistics support and spare parts, things of this sort, to keep their airplanes flying.
Right, yeah.
Yeah, we were talking about this yesterday.
And you were talking about the relationships that you had, or the relations that you had with the Japanese bureaucrats now that Japan was an independent nation.
Could you touch on that?

Well you had almost a twice a week meeting with the chief of staff of the Japanese Air Defense Force General Sanagi and I would say at least once a month my staff along with my staff would make field trips go out to the various Japanese bases and really get on the spot
look at how they were doing rather than just looking at the mechanics, statistics that were sent in.
And I probably operated a little differently because in my inspection procedures I would open drawers and open doors that were closed just to see what was
what kind of skeletons were in the closets.
And as I mentioned yesterday, this is where I found numerous starters, generators, spare parts that were inoperable, but could be repaired.
And although the Japanese didn't particularly like that method, they condoned it.
Say the American taxpayers, I would imagine.
What did your superiors think of that?
Well, they thought that was a real good idea.

I mean, because they really hadn't thought about the fact that the Japanese labor pay scale was such that they could economically repair these if the United States provided them with the bits and pieces to do the overhauling.
And we established a program like that.
How did you get along with the Japanese people now that you went back ten years after?
Well, the Japanese people were always, to me, very courteous.
I'm sure that we in the United States would have been belligerent
whereas the Japanese thought well we must have something and they wanted to copy us.
And I got along with the Japanese real well.
What was the quality of their Air Force in the late 1950s?
Well they really had, see we provided
them with the F-86.
Now the F-86 was an obsolete airplane, almost.
It's what you'd probably call a second line airplane when we ride it with them.
And it was probably a good stepping stone.
It certainly wasn't up to the F-100 that we were using on our bases.
But it was a real good training vehicle.
I would say that we got our money's worth out of the F-86s that we provided them.
Did they complain that they were getting second rate or used equipment?
No, I mean, I guess they didn't want to look a gift horse in the mouth.
They were being given to them, so they were... And we provided logistic support for them.
And, of course, we shipped them a lot of stuff that they probably didn't need, like
when the F-86 was first purchased while we anticipated so many wing changes.
Well, it didn't turn out that we needed nearly as much replacement wings as we anticipated, but we shipped the Japanese all these wings, so they had to store them.
So we had warehouse after warehouse full of wings that
would never do really them any good.
What'd they do with them?
What'd they do?
They stored them.
Probably still have them.
Yeah, they still have them.
And the other thing with the Japanese and looking back at them, we provided them with computers on stock control and things of this sort.
But they really didn't at that time believe in computers.
They still kept everything by hand.
Every, almost every

nut bolt and screw that when we repaired an airplane why we had a bench stock that we just rolled out to the airplane and used whatever we needed and when we got back in why somebody replaced, poured some more screws in there without counting them or anything of this sort.
Japanese they counted every bolt, every screw, everything that was used.
I mean it's, they did it very meticulous.
And so they kept our system and they continued to use their old system that they had been using for years and years and years.
I bet you were happy to become the commander of the 39th Air Division to get your own command again.
Yeah, I worked at that.
How?
Well, I went over to see Joan Burns and see if he had an opening.
And they kept in touch with the commander of 5th Air Force.
And I was always out.
I had to go out to see him at least once a week anyway on briefing monostas of the Japanese air because they were part of the defense of Japan.
And we depended on them to patrol certain segments of certain areas of Japan.
And so I was out there about once a week to a staff meeting.
So I just... To give them the elbow.
Yeah, well, that's part of your duty, and also during that time you could promote a job.
Now, let's talk about Japanese air defenses.
What percentage of the total air defense was American?
What percent was
Japanese.
How'd you work that relationship?
Oh, I would say that during that period of time they were just becoming combat.
I would probably estimate maybe 25 percent.
Like the Japanese had Hokkaido and Misawa was the most northern American base.
So we turned over all of the
the air defense of Hokkaido to them.
Then there were other areas over on the Sea of Japan that they had air bases over there that they could scramble fighters for intercept.
So it was
Well, we were tied into their air command and their control centers too.
It was just a joint cooperative effort, sort of like NATO?
Well, yeah, you had, like Basava, we had an air division headquarters of the Japanese Air Self Defense Force, and then we had an air division headquarters of the Air Force.
And jointly we had a control center.
And we ran a control center next door.
The Japanese ran their control center so that they all were just tied together.
And of course, we and our GCA, our ground controlled approaches, instrument landing type of thing,
why the Japanese had their own and we had our own.
The Japanese, we taught them English.
Yeah, I was going to ask about that.
What about the language barrier?
But when the Japanese really got into stress of why they'd go to Japanese, so you didn't know what they were saying particularly.
Was there much of a language barrier?
I would say the same as in almost any foreign country where you have a completely foreign language.
I took a language course in Japanese and my wife did so that we at least could talk to
the politicians or the individuals who didn't speak any English at all.
Oh, could you?
I mean, you could start a conversation?
Yeah, you could carry on a reasonable conversation as to the courtesies of the day.
And they gave you a sort of a staff and wife officer program?
Or how did they work it?
And was it stressed?
This is through the Air Force, right?
No, well, the wives and getting back to the mag.
Yeah.
While Johnson Augie and all his chiefs, their wives would come out and take cooking lessons from the Americans.
Really?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
So they... From the American wives?
Yeah, from my wife and...
and the other members of the MAG staff.
And they in turn would run a Japanese-English course.
And then of course I had as my right hand a Nisi that was fluent in Japanese and fluent in English.
So, and he accompanied me almost every, he did accommodate me everywhere I went.
So, you always had somebody who could bail you out as far as the language program was concerned.
And you had the same thing.
Was he a civilian or was he in the Air Force?
He was a civilian.
He was a civilian.
all properties, GS-9, GS-11.
He was a civil service civilian.
He was American.
And then each section, the operations, and each one of them had an interpreter so that when they went out by themselves, they could take someone with them.
You were talking earlier about Curtis LeMay
and how he stressed how important it was for the staff wives to welcome others into the Air Force community, things like that.
And then you mentioned again here about your wife and the wives of the Japanese generals getting together.
Was there a lot of this social contact with the Japanese and with the relations very good in that sense?
Oh, yeah.
When I was on the embassy staff at that time, you had, you were always a lot more than I really enjoyed.
Cocktail parties, or anybody who came in, high ranking Air Force, my Japanese always wine and diamond.
and you were a part of that program.
And then of course the Cherry Blossom time, they always invited you to, gave you tickets to that and you got a grand reception and a front seat on that time.
No, they pampered you quite a bit.
Well, I mean it was in their best interest that they do pamper you quite a bit.
And that was just, it seemed to me, part of your duty.
And when you got up to 5th Air Force, it was more of a formal type of thing.
When a Japanese general came up to inspect the Japanese, sometimes they wouldn't even contact you.
However,
At Misawa we established a maintenance program that, well we went nine months without an aircraft accident, but a single airplane accident.
So the Japanese were very interested in that.
So everybody and his brother from the Japanese Air Defense Force came up to copy what you were looking at.
What were you doing?
What were you doing right?
Nine months you had, as a commander of the 39th Air Division, you had 100 jet aircraft and you had nine months without a single accident.
You must have been doing something right.
Well, the first thing I did when I first got up there is, and you probably couldn't do that in this day and age, but I had the judge give me a list of all the names of individuals who had been
picked up drunken disorderly at least two times and any other serious offense.
And I just, and then I had... Enlisted men and officers?
Enlisted, no, the highest ranking was a lieutenant colonel.
And there were various type of offenses.
sleeping with a Japanese girl when he had a wife and kids and this type of thing.
I mean, I just didn't tolerate that type of thing.
So I just shipped them all home.
Really?
Oh, yeah.
You could ship them all.
I shipped about 250 home.
You shipped 250?
How many you had here as the commander?
You had 13,000 personnel here.
as a commander under your responsibility.
And you shipped 250 of them home, officers and men?
Two officers and men.
And a lot of these men were career men.
Well, see, General Burns, when he gave me the job, he said, Tex, I'll give you three months.
And that outfit up there is being operated kind of a country club.
and their accident rate was about to worsen the Air Force.
Really?
And so I granted all the airplanes, first thing.
And then I talked to every Okay, why did you do that?
Well, because they were Why did you ground them all immediately?
Weren't properly maintained.
Okay, okay.
You wanted to get them back on a maintenance schedule.
Then I got the master sergeants, the supervisors, and we unbuttoned.

every airplane inspected gave them a real thorough inspection and looked for cracks and so you got all the technical man you got all the people out of the offices who were real professionals out on the front line looking at airplanes and then then you took this program of shipping all these people home and
and that really is very drastic.
It goes over the base real thoroughly.
I remember the day I arrived up there I was picked up at the airport and I was driving to my quarters and there was some sergeant that just looked at you and you had a star on your
and he didn't salute, didn't do anything.
So I stopped, backed up, and got out and chewed him out a little bit.
Was he a guard?
No, he was just a sergeant, just looking.
Maybe he was so shocked to see a general coming in.
Well, he had a general commanded before.
And then one of the squadron commanders, I picked him up on base for speeding.
I was following him in my civilian car at the time.
It was probably two or three weeks later.
And I chewed him out.
And of course the Lois and the two girls were with me then, so they kind of ducked down.
They didn't want anybody to see them while I was doing my duty.
And I just didn't want anybody who was going out getting drunk all night and working on airplanes during the daytime.
In fact, I had a young airman come in.
He said, I said, John, I said, I'm sorry that I'm going home.
I wish I, well, I weren't, but I'm sure that if you had been here, I wouldn't be sent home.
I mean, the standards were such that you just thought that was the thing to do, or no one really cared.
What did you say, how did you answer that?
Well I said, well I'm sorry you have to go home too, but I said that's the way, I said you can get over this, it's no problem.
I mean being sent home before being drunk is disorderly, why if you just take it in stride and not,
make you think that you are a complete failure.
Why, you're really not.
I mean, it's just one of those obstacles that you have to face.
What rank was this?
This is an enlisted man?
Oh, he was about a corporal or something.
A real clean-cut young man.
And you could, you probably could have begged exception.
But you make an exception to him, why do you have to beg exception to everybody else?
And we worked out pretty well, because only
Only about two or three congressional inquiries came in.
You always had the problem of congressional inquiries.
Somebody's parents write their congressman, and your congressman writes their secretary of defense, and the secretary of defense comes on down.
It just happened that the three that they inquired about were the worst offenders.
I mean, you know, therefore, I got off real... And I'll agree that we probably sent 25% home that we could have...
of probably improve and they would have never done it again.
Now what do you mean when you say you sent them home?
You sent them to a base in the States?
No, you had authority on the Air Force regulations at the time to discharge individuals who did not become accustomed to the Air Force live.
It was a real easy program to have.
So these people were discharged?
They were discharged from the Air Force.
Dishonorable or undesirable or general?
Undesirable.
Really?
Well, I say a general.
It wasn't a good conduct discharge.
It was the next lower level.
A general discharge?
Yeah.
And then after you get your airplanes inspected, and then after you get the people who are carousing out of your way, well then you can start building an Air Force.
And before I went up there, I'd gone over to the Fifth Air Force and made up little cards on each individual, and got a picture, and also what is the,
efficiency reports were, so that when I got up there, I knew who the officers were that had the most, that had the best record, and the captains, the majors, the lieutenant colonels.
And so I looked at the standpoint of the standardization team that tested everybody, all the pilots, as to whether or not they were doing a good job.
And I got rid of the ones that were average and put in the outstanding pilots that had the best records in there.
And then we started through and tested every pilot.
We tested every pilot.
And my position was on emergency exams, 98 is not good enough.
I mean, you have to make 100.
If you have an emergency exam and you fail two procedures, why, you just... Yeah, so you just, I insisted on 100%.
And we set up some skill programs like tic-tac-toe programs so that each pilots would test each other by...
by questions on airplane systems and flying techniques and things of this sort against each other.
I got the wives clubs and the NCO wives clubs involved in setting up a ward program so that your crew chief who had
had his airplane on the line ready to fly and flew his mission in any one month, why you give him a void of a hundred dollars or a trip for he and his wife down to Tokyo and this type of thing.
I bet you that increased morale.
Oh yeah.
And whether or not they were colored or white or what have you didn't really make any difference.
The procedure was that the one that
Well, I set up a program, and this is a SAC program, what you'd call a tail number schedule.
Each airplane had a number, 1, 2, 7, 6, 7, 7, 6, 8, 7, 6, 9, on down.
And then on the first of the month, prior to the first of the month, you'd set up a schedule.
That airplane was going to fly on the 3rd, the 8th, the 14th, the 4-hour mission, or whatever the mission was.
And if the crew chief had that airplane ready to fly on the day they were scheduled to fly, and it flew all its missions during the month, then he was in competition for the best crew chief on base.
And then the other thing is whatever discrepancies the pilot wrote up at the end of the mission.
And then you'd get down and he flew his missions and no discrepancies as well.
So sometimes you'd have a tie.
But anyway, that got the airplanes in good condition.
Where'd you get the money for this, to send the guy and his wife down to Tokyo?
Well, the Oscars Wives Club and the NCO Wives Club, see, they had programs and cake sales and they had...
They raised the money.
I didn't care how they raised it.
And then the commanders, each commander had a, I shouldn't call it a slush fund, he had a commander's fund that he could use for either entertainment or visiting dignitaries or what have you.
And that was a big thing.
Go down and pay somebody's train trip down and you had hotels in Tokyo that were taken over by the Air Force so they could stay at a rest hotel at two dollars a day or something of this sort.
So that was a good big, big boost on morale.
And then you work on the wives.
The pilots, well if they drink a little too much

one particular day why then he says they shouldn't be really be flying the next day so so you depending on the wives to help you out if he's going to fly the next day why keep him keep him off the bottle during the day during the night or during that evening and and did you go around and talk to the wives or did you oh i talked to i had a meeting of all the wives and that's one of the uh
speeches as I let you read on that Basava wasn't as bad as all this, that happiness is not where you is, not a matter of geography type of thing.
I made a talk to all the incoming wives and
And I was probably... Of officers and enlisted?
And enlisted.
My goodness, you had 1,700 families there.
Yeah, but see... You would have been talking almost every day.
Well, no, 1,700, see, but you...
Families, yeah.
You just talk to them one time, and then you only talk to the ones that are coming in, the replacements, see?
So maybe in one month, maybe you had only 20 new families arrive.
So it's not really that...
I see.
So you just set up a meeting for those 20 at the end of the month?
Yeah, you just set up a meeting and talked to the NCO wives and the officers' wives together, new families that came in.
And you also normally talk to the officers and enlisted men who came in to get them.
When I first arrived up there, I talked to every, I made a speech to every
every individual on base.
Tell them that I'm not the former commander.
I'm a different type of individual.
And I gave my philosophy on that I really didn't mind people drinking, but I detested the drunk.
I mean, this type of thing.
And that I expected if you're going to be
pilot, I expect you to be the best pilot.
And we're going to make this the best base in the Air Force.
And we're going to not have any accidents.
I mean it's just absolutely ridiculous to have an accident when an engine quits or something of this sort when it could be aborted.
And I
preach a little conservatism that if something was wrong with your airplane, don't push on.
Come back to base and land.
The safest place is on the ground and there will be another day to fly.
And so they brought back airplanes that had to be continued while probably the engine would have quit or something of that sort.
So you
set up competition between squadrons on bombing competition and efficiency programs.
And you had the best pilots.
You had a roster in each squadron listing the best pilot, the best bombing pilot, and then the fighters.
And so you could have them competing against each other.
And it worked real good, I mean actually.
And we had, well we had a lot of colored pilots at that time, not a lot I'd say, but we had- About what percentage?
Oh I'd say maybe, well one of the squadrons,
